Since there is only one source, all cells are assigned the same color.

 

Constraints:

1 <= n, m <= 10^5
1 <= n * m <= 10^5
1 <= sources.length <= n * m
sources[i] = [ri, ci, colori]
0 <= ri <= n - 1
0 <= ci <= m - 1
1 <= colori <= 10^6‚Äã‚Äã‚Äã‚Äã‚Äã‚Äã‚Äã
All (ri, ci‚Äã‚Äã‚Äã‚Äã‚Äã‚Äã‚Äã) in sources are distinct.

Code : // O(n*m)

class Solution {
    public int[][] colorGrid(int n, int m, int[][] sources) {
        int[][] grid = new int[n][m];
        Queue<int[]> q = new LinkedList<>();

        // Initialize sources
        for (int[] s : sources) {
            int r = s[0], c = s[1], color = s[2];
            grid[r][c] = color;
            q.offer(new int[] { r, c });
        }

        int[][] dirs = { { 1, 0 }, { -1, 0 }, { 0, 1 }, { 0, -1 } };

        while (!q.isEmpty()) {
            int size = q.size();

            // store next level updates (resolve conflicts)
            Map<Integer, int[]> next = new HashMap<>();

            for (int i = 0; i < size; i++) {
                int[] cell = q.poll();
                int r = cell[0], c = cell[1];
                int color = grid[r][c];

                for (int[] d : dirs) {
                    int nr = r + d[0];
                    int nc = c + d[1];

                    if (nr < 0 || nc < 0 || nr >= n || nc >= m)
                        continue;
                    if (grid[nr][nc] != 0)
                        continue;

                    int key = nr * m + nc;

                    // pick max color for conflicts
                    if (!next.containsKey(key) || next.get(key)[2] < color) {
                        next.put(key, new int[] { nr, nc, color });
                    }
                }
            }

            // apply updates
            for (int[] val : next.values()) {
                int r = val[0], c = val[1], color = val[2];
                grid[r][c] = color;
                q.offer(new int[] { r, c });
            }
        }

        return grid;
    }
}
